"Reich N.H., Alsema E.A., Van Sark W.G.J.H.M., Turkenburg W.C., Sinke W.C.","Greenhouse gas emissions associated with photovoltaic electricity from crystalline silicon modules under various energy supply options",2011,"Progress in Photovoltaics: Research and Applications","19","5",,"603","613",,,10.1002/pip.1066,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960029973&partnerID=40&md5=7034ce9bd8f426186fa710fd159ee519","Department of Science, Technology and Society, Copernicus Institute, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS, Utrecht, Netherlands; Energy Research Centre of the Netherlands (ECN), Petten, Netherlands","Reich, N.H., Department of Science, Technology and Society, Copernicus Institute, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS, Utrecht, Netherlands; Alsema, E.A., Department of Science, Technology and Society, Copernicus Institute, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS, Utrecht, Netherlands; Van Sark, W.G.J.H.M., Department of Science, Technology and Society, Copernicus Institute, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS, Utrecht, Netherlands; Turkenburg, W.C., Department of Science, Technology and Society, Copernicus Institute, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS, Utrecht, Netherlands; Sinke, W.C., Department of Science, Technology and Society, Copernicus Institute, Utrecht University, Heidelberglaan 2, 3584 CS, Utrecht, Netherlands, Energy Research Centre of the Netherlands (ECN), Petten, Netherlands","The direct and indirect emissions associated with photovoltaic (PV) electricity generation are evaluated, focussing on greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions related to crystalline silicon (c-Si) solar module production. Electricity supply technologies used in the entire PV production chain are found to be most influential. Emissions associated with only the electricity-input in the production of PV vary as much as 0-200 g CO2-eq per kWh electricity generated by PV. This wide range results because of specific supply technologies one may assume to provide the electricity-input in PV production, i.e., whether coal-, gas-, wind-, or PV-power facilities in the ""background"" provide the electricity supply for powering the entire PV production chain. The heat input in the entire PV production chain, for which mainly the combustion of natural gas is assumed, adds another ∼16 CO 2-eq/kWh. The GHG emissions directly attributed to c-Si PV technology alone constitute only ∼1-2 g CO2-eq/kWh. The difference in scale indicates the relevance of reporting ""indirect"" emissions due to energy input in PV production separately from ""direct"" emissions particular to PV technology. In this article, we also demonstrate the utilization of ""direct"" and ""indirect"" shares of emissions for the calculation of GHG emissions in simplified world electricity- and PV-market development scenarios. Results underscore very large GHG mitigation realized by solar PV toward increasingly significant PV market shares. Copyright © 2011 John Wiley &amp; Sons, Ltd.","CO2; energy transition; global warming; LCA; photovoltaic; PV emissions","Crystalline silicons; Development scenarios; Electricity supply; Energy inputs; Energy supplies; Energy transitions; GHG emission; GHG mitigation; Heat input; LCA; Market share; photovoltaic; Photovoltaic electricities; Production chain; PV emissions; Solar module; Solar PVs; Associated gas; Carbon dioxide; Coal combustion; Competition; Crystalline materials; Electric generators; Electricity; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Photovoltaic effects; Solar energy; Solar power generation; Technology; Gas emissions",,,,,,"Azzopardi, B., Mutale, J., Life cycle analysis for future photovoltaic systems using hybrid solar cells (2010) Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews, 14 (3), pp. 1130-1134; Alsema, E.A., Wild-Scholten, M., Reduction of the environmental impacts in crystalline silicon module manufacturing (2007) Proceedings of 22nd European Photovoltaic Solar Energy Conference, pp. 829-